An '''autogenous weld''' is a form of [[welding]], where the filler material is either supplied by melting the base material, or is of identical composition.<ref name="Copper, 29" /> The weld may be formed entirely by melting parts of the base metal and no additional [[filler rod]] is used.
There is some variation in the use of this term. Those bodies concerned with teaching the craft skill of welding tend to define it as using no filler rod, i.e. the technique is based purely on the base metal. Those concerned with the welded joint's [[metallurgy]] may make no distinction between a filler rod and the base metal, provided that the final metallurgy is identical.<ref name="Copper, 29" />
Most welding processes may be either autogenous, or may use additional filler. Some are characteristically autogenous and avoid filler. Some [[arc welding]] processes, including such major process such as [[manual metal arc welding|Manual Metal Arc]] (stick) welding and [[gas metal arc welding|MAGS]] (wire-feed) welding, cannot be used autogenously, as they rely on the consumption of a filler rod to provide the arc.
Some processes are typically autogenous. These include some [[gas welding]] processes such as [[lead burning]] (although fillers may optionally be used) and [[oxy-acetylene welding]] in some positions, such as [[seam welding]] the edges of two overlapping sheets. [[Resistance welding]], both [[spot welding]] and [[seam welding]], is inherently autogenous as there is no convenient way to apply a filler. [[Friction welding|Friction]] and [[laser welding]] have similar restrictions.
Some alloys are prone to changing their composition when heated, particularly a loss of [[zinc]] from [[brass]] by its evaporation as vapour. In these cases, an excess of 2–3% extra zinc may be provided in the filler rod to compensate.{{sfnp|Welding, Brazing and Soldering of Copper and its Alloys|1952|pages=83–84}} Silicon may also be used as an additive to reduce this loss.{{sfnp|Welding, Brazing and Soldering of Copper and its Alloys|1952|pages=83–84}}
A few materials, such as the [[HY-80#Weldability|HY-80]] series of high-strength steels, require a non-autogenous process to control their metallurgy.<ref name="Roepke, 2009" /> However advanced processes, such as [[hybrid laser arc welding]], have been used to achieve the same effect autogenously.<ref name="Roepke, 2009" />
