'''Non-radiative life time''' is the average time before an [[electron]] in the [[conduction band]] of a [[semiconductor]] [[carrier generation and recombination|recombines]] with a [[electron hole|hole]] non-radiatively. It is an important parameter in [[optoelectronics]] where [[radiative recombination]] is required to produce a [[photon]]; if the non-radiative life time is shorter than the radiative, then a carrier is more likely to [[non-radiative recombination|recombine non-radiatively]]. This results in low internal [[quantum efficiency]].

