{{Infobox laboratory |name = PEDRO Center |native_name = |image = PEDRO_Center_Logo.png |latin_name = |motto = |established = 2017 |type = [[Satellite ground station]] |budget = |debt = |research_field = |president = |vice-president = |director = |head_label = |head = |faculty = |staff = |postdoc = |address = |city = [[Quezon City]], [[Metro Manila]] |province = |country = [[Philippines]] |coor = {{coor|14.647219|N|121.0719533|E|display=inline,title}} |zipcode = |campus = <!---no source yet if the station is to be built within the UP Diliman campus---> |free_label = |free = |nickname = |affiliations = [[Department of Science and Technology (Philippines)|Department of Science and Technology]] |operating_agency = {{nowrap|Advanced Science and Technology Institute}} |nobel_laureates = |website = <!-- {{URL|}} --> |logo = |footnotes = }}
The '''Philippine Earth Data Resources Observation Center''', also known as the '''PEDRO Center''', is a [[satellite ground station]] situated at the [[Department of Science and Technology (Philippines)|Department of Science and Technology]]–Advanced Science and Technology Institute (DOST–ASTI) facility at the [[University of Philippines Diliman]] in [[Quezon City]], [[Philippines]].<ref name="diwata2better">{{cite news|last1=Usman|first1=Edd|title=How Diwata-2 is better than PH's first satellite, Diwata-1|url=http://www.rappler.com/technology/features/171988-diwata-1-diwata-2-improvements-up-tech-fair|accessdate=6 June 2017|work=Rappler|date=5 June 2017}}</ref>
It is part of the [[Philippine Scientific Earth Observation Microsatellite program|Philippine Scientific Earth Observation Micro-satellite]] (Phil-Microsat) program by the [[Department of Science and Technology (Philippines)|Department of Science and Technology]], which includes the deployment of the [[Diwata-1]] and [[Diwata-2]] microsatellites.<ref name=pdisettogo>{{cite news|last1=Yee|first1=Jovic|title=1st PH-made satellite set to go into space|url=http://globalnation.inquirer.net/134922/1st-ph-made-satellite-set-to-go-into-space|accessdate=13 January 2016|work=Philippine Daily Inquirer|date=12 January 2015}}</ref> It also receives information from commercial satellites.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Icamina|first1=Paul|title=‘Diwata’ a step closer to orbit|url=http://www.malaya.com.ph/business-news/news/%E2%80%98diwata%E2%80%99-step-closer-orbit|accessdate=28 March 2016|publisher=Malaya|date=28 March 2016}}</ref>
The ground station was initially planned to be located inside the [[Subic Bay Freeport Zone]] in [[Subic, Zambales|Subic]], [[Zambales]].<ref name=rappler1>{{cite news|last1=Ranada|first1=Pia|title=Introducing Diwata, the first Philippine-made satellite|url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/86327-philippine-microsatellite-diwata|accessdate=12 March 2015|publisher=Rappler|date=10 March 2015}}</ref> This plan was reportedly changed in March 2016, with the ground station to be built in [[Diliman]], [[Quezon City]] instead. Construction began in 2016<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ronda|first1=Rainier Allan|title=US aircraft with Philippines’s first microsatellite launched into space|url=http://www.philstar.com:8080/headlines/2016/03/24/1566175/us-aircraft-philippiness-first-microsatellite-launched-space|accessdate=28 March 2016|publisher=The Philippine Star|date=24 March 2016}}</ref> and PEDRO became operational by June 2017.<ref name="diwata2better"/>
