{{orphan|date=April 2018}} '''Solvated Metal Atom Dispersion''' is a method of producing highly reactive<ref name="Sergeev"></ref> [[Solvation|solvated]] [[nanoparticle]]s. Samples of the metal (or [[ceramic]])<ref name="Sergeev" /> are heated to produce free atoms (or [[Chemical species|species]]), as in [[Evaporation_(deposition)|PVD evaporation]]. These are then co-depositied with a suitable organic frozen [[solvent]] (eg. [[toluene]])<ref name="Schubert"></ref> at very low temperatures (on the order of 70K).<ref name="Klabunde"></ref> This is then warmed towards room temperature, producing solvated metal ions or (over time) larger clusters. Sometimes, catalysts supports (such as [[SiO2|SiO<sub>2</sub>]] or [[Al2O3|Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub>]]) are added to improve [[nucleation]],<ref name="Li"></ref> as it can more readily take place on surface [[OH group]]s.
